{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"api_error_status":null,"duration_ms":177933,"duration_api_ms":142510,"ttft_ms":2704,"ttft_stream_ms":2701,"time_to_request_ms":504,"num_turns":19,"result":"The curl returns `hello` with exit code 0. HTTPS access is restored.\n\n## Summary\n\n**Root cause:** The `demo-ingress` Ingress for `demo.example.com` referenced a TLS secret (`expired-tls-secret`) containing a certificate that was both **expired** (valid only Jan 1–2, **2020**) and signed by a **stale/wrong \"Test CA\"** that did not match the CA clients actually trust (`/tmp/tls/ca.crt` mounted in the `curl-test` pod). This caused the `SSL certificate problem: unable to get local issuer certificate` validation failures, even though the `echo-server` backend was healthy.\n\n**Diagnosis path:**\n1. Inspected the ingress → it pointed at `expired-tls-secret`.\n2. Extracted the cert → expired in 2020, issuer `Test CA` but failed `openssl verify` against the trusted CA.\n3. Discovered the *real* trusted CA was the one mounted inside the `curl-test` pod (`/tmp/tls/ca.crt`, SKI `83:B5...`), which differed from a stale host-side CA. An earlier candidate (`new-tls.crt`) was signed by the wrong CA and still failed.\n4. Located the matching CA private key (`/tmp/test-ca.key`) by modulus comparison against the pod's CA.\n\n**Fix:**\n- Issued a fresh `demo.example.com` leaf certificate (SAN `DNS:demo.example.com`, valid 2026→2028, serverAuth) signed by the correct CA (`test-ca.key`/`test-ca.crt`).\n- Created secret `demo-tls-valid` with the new cert/key and pointed `demo-ingress`'s `spec.tls[0].secretName` at it.\n\n**Verification:** nginx now serves the valid cert, and the in-cluster curl against `https://demo.example.com` with `--cacert /tmp/tls/ca.crt` returns `hello` with **exit code 0**.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"901d570e-a61e-480e-b5c5-48e2083fab89","total_cost_usd":1.059438,"usage":{"input_tokens":3027,"cache_creation_input_tokens":39726,"cache_read